A Republican Strategy to Counter Obama's Re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, claiming that electoral fraud is rarer in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
Republican lawyers have reported only 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of U.S. governments enacted new laws starting in 2009 that made the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon gained momentum after the November 2010 elections, which saw the addition of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced in 2011 alone.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce advance voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on polling day, and remove citizens with a judicial record from voting rights.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to set such a requirement.
In 2008, the U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana law.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card like the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo ID cards issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 did not have such an identity document.
However, it often costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required identity card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect youth, minorities, and low-income people.
25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID.
More than that.
Students, considered to be more likely to vote for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs to vote.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to make such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic vote.
Two out of three Hispanic voters favor the Democratic Party.
Republican lawmakers sponsored laws in 2011 abolishing voter registration on polling day in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequence.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped register about 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the registration rate of new voters by 17 per cent in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have enacted laws in five other states to reduce the advance voting period.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African Americans, while the latter represented only 13% of the state’s voters.
The same was true of Hispanics.
These represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
On the other hand, whites who made up 76% of voters represented only 46% of voters voting in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters strongly opposed the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by vetoes from Democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to limit the damage in part.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
Nevertheless, the new rules put in place will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that were passed and see it as an obvious goal to influence the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that the states that passed these laws accounted for 171 of the 270 votes needed for the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Screening for prostate cancer: pass the test or not?
