Another study, the European one, concluded that there was a difference in mortality between patients who had been screened and those who did not.
This study also showed, with follow-up after 12 years, that we are between 30 and 40% more likely to have metastases if we are not detected.
So I recommend the test from age 50, or from age 40 if you have a direct parent who has already had prostate cancer.
Men of African-American descent are also more at risk.
The key is to make the right decision once a cancer has been detected.
There are aggressive cancers and others that are indolent.
The degree of risk of cancer must be made clear to the patient, by offering possible options, by not necessarily treating prostate cancers that do not harm life in the long term, and by opting instead, in these cases, for active surveillance of the disease.
Today, many men in whom cancer is detected will not be treated, because their cancer is not aggressive and does not threaten their lives.
We're going to suggest they do active surveillance and if the disease progresses, we're going to offer them treatment.
Increasingly, criteria for deciding who should or should not be dealt with are being precisely determined.
I recommend taking the test anyway.
