The Higgs Boson
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created quite a stir last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, just that.
And then, it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "least worst" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we hold an authentic new particle, and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, but data is still lacking to be perfectly certain.
Suppose, however, that it is the Higgs, since the chances of making a mistake seem slim, and let's see what it is.
There is, in this lower world, a fatally unavoidable law that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There's no way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
But even if particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting roughly of some of their characteristics.
From here, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In one corner are good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey the principle of Pauli.
And in the other are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least not for this principle, which means that they can be in the same place, at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure, of Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not address here, and the "particles of force", through which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, it must be pointed out here, are not all as exotic as one might think.
In fact, if you can read this column, it is thanks to a boson of an extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light" that is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field in that precise place, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "disturbance" arises an electromagnetic wave (from light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
More stable field
The same is true of the Higgs boson, except that it is another field, the Higgs field, which must be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to reach very, very high energies, a bit as if it were a frozen pond of which only a very large rock could ride the surface.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN's - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring 27 km in circumference! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
Not all particles, not all materials, interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don't - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold of itself on a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the others (like the photon, you know) do not.
Now, what "can bring" all this research, asks Ms. Plamondon?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any discrepancies between observations and predictions of the MS.
There are also many who ardently wish that we find them, because the slightest difference could open a door on a "new physics" and plug certain holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, offering no explanation for gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-oops!).
But no such gaps have been found at CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of this research on the daily lives of Mr. and Mrs. All-World are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be none.
At the very beginning of the 1960s, the laser pioneers at Bell Laboratories did not suspect the revolution that their work was going to trigger.
They were looking at scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, physicist Willard Boyle — who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed), in 1962 — told us beforehand that the laser was rather seen as a "lab gadget".
Imagine...
And then, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his work in optics.
This sensor, although it was not at all his original intention, now serves as an "eye" to all the digital cameras in the world, and earned him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This of course does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it does mean that, really, we never know...
