With its Commission dying in dignity, Quebec recently debated the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate is due to resume shortly as a bill is being prepared.
In this crucial area, however, much remains to be done.
The Duty tried to take a closer look.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his Montérégie apartment.
The prostate cancer that gnawed on him had left him a two-year respite.
"They had given me five years to live, I turned seven," he said, half-fig-half-grape, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home, Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
“But it’s always a shock, you can’t be prepared for that,” he says.
Disease does its work: a huge weakness that prevents it from going to the toilet alone, and even eating alone.
Lying in front of an appetizing lunch, he agreed to let himself be helped to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even manages to smile, speaks to strangers who work around him, bring him his medications, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My greatest wish is to be cured of diarrhea, it’s humiliating,” he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
“In the course of our lives, we learn that a man pisses standing up,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois house.
Regressing to the child stage, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
"It depends on the ability of the person" to accept regression, he notes.
Because, in the opinion of several people working in palliative care, great moments take place at the very heart of this regression.
Patients who enter the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provides so-called "curative" care.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "consciously and stifled".
But the disease made me discover my children.
“I have good children,” she adds.
“I don’t have any wishes in life anymore,” she said, before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
In the coming days, however, she awaits a final visit from her son from Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, we spend, with a group of volunteers, body care and food assistance.
It is palliative care, which is given when there is nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed per 11,700 inhabitants.
It's very little when you know that we all end up dying one day.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the house.
Whether in terms of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
When dying, we will agree to provide mouth care with brandy or Pepsi, as requested.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we served a beer to Mr. X, who died overnight.
This morning, it is his son who will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We help the loved ones as much as the patients,” says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, the days follow each other but are not alike.
Alongside a 93-year-old man who enjoys his last family gathering in the courtyard, snuggled in his pillows while being trinched in his honor, a 36-year-old man dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, after having tried everything to survive.
"For six months, there are still three to five beds that are occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45," Dr Christiane Martel said.
53% of patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home arrive from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, to care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient has reached the terminal stage of his or her life, whether at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as Victor-Gadbois House and the Société de société de soins palliatives <0xC3><0xA0> domicile du Grand Montréal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care offered to cancer patients.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec health care that has caused many doctors specializing in palliative care to fear the adoption of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care leaders including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has circulated to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not performing well enough to ensure that everyone will be entitled to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
Recently, she said, I saw a patient spend 14 days in the emergency room, in great pain, without doing what was necessary to relieve her.
I fear that patients will ask to die only because they do not receive adequate care.
And at the same time, several oncologists struggle with their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Helene Richard's hopes for survival were already low when she dropped out of strenuous chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she replied that she regretted that I stopped fighting, she said.
Yet she told me I was finished!
No all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank caregivers for not acceding to their request after they have been relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Society for Palliative Care at Home in Greater Montreal, patients would be refractory to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which amounts to putting the patient to sleep until the moment of death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
Patients who are not relieved always say the same sentence: “I want to die.”
But it doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to euthanize me,” it means “I want to be relieved.”
