The price of bitcoin, after reaching a peak of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to 2 dollars, five months later, before returning today around ten dollars (the prices are listed on the site bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing very impressive compared to global exchanges in real currency or financial products.
Yet the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She describes bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency”, “competiting with the dollar or the euro” and “similar to conventional currencies”.
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currency such as "credits", used to progress in a video game that you win by playing or that you can buy (and sometimes exchange in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed this kind of system.
But, each time, a central authority controls and processes the exchanges.
With Bitcoin, all nodes in the network are both bookkeepers, auditors, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually done between two e-mail addresses in the manner of an e-mail.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins do exist in the public ledger, distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It involves solving a mathematical challenge to computers, the winner of which, as a sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a file hashing phase, that is, transforming a large file into a shorter and unique digital fingerprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before "shaking" the whole.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular imprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the footprint.
If, to cheat, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphaned because the two have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the challenge won 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to the one hundred millionth, which leaves some margin...
The difficulty of the challenge is also noted with each increase in computing power.
Network life has already had ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins stolen in deposits.
"The flaw used is not about the protocol itself," said Pierre Noizat, who just launched Paymium, a real-currency payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this flaw.
Powerful actors like Wikipedia refuse donations of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins are not circulating.
In November, "giant balances" were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” said Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of an educational book on this currency, strongly believes in the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus return cheaper.
The bearer also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
They just need to communicate an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement to question hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
“It will take time for Bitcoin to impose itself, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
The ECB, in its report, also plans to reassess the various risks, now considered high, in case of success of this currency.
We left Afghanistan.
What's next?
The French troops left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the United States are expected to follow at the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to take back its territory and for the Afghans to choose their future, without expecting anything from us.
It is mainly the Afghan peasants that we punished by considering them terrorists.
And ourselves, with our 88 soldiers killed, and the wounded, maimed.
The Taliban are made up of foreign extremists, former chief refugees in Pakistan, but often peasants who refuse foreign armed presence, as in Soviet times.
They want to defend their traditions, ancient and archaic, even if they were joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks, Tajiks.
Tolerated, sometimes aided by local insurgents, they will no longer be tolerated when Westerners become more discreet.
The departure of the French troops from the base of Nijrab, which I observed from the top of the hills planted with almond trees thanks to French credits, took place in order.
The convoys of trucks and armored vehicles reached Kabul without being attacked, overflew by helicopters.
There will be no Taliban raids on Kabul by the end of 2014.
Circumstances have changed since their irresistible advance from 1994 to 1996.
Kabul was then empty, the country on fire and in blood because of the struggles between different factions.
Their takeover of the country had then been perceived as a kind of liberation, a return to security.
Afghans have paid the price for the obscurantism of these peasants overwhelmed by the Al-Qaeda organization, but their situation has not improved today.
Former mujahideen, Afghan government and current Taliban join in the desire to keep women in an inferior position.
The main notables of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They turned into businessmen, seizing government land to resell to refugees returning from Iran and Pakistan, benefiting from huge U.S. subcontracting contracts.
They disdained themselves; most of them did not fight themselves.
People, as I heard in the countryside, aspire to a government that is not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave, as will those who have been able to take advantage of the American riches: the flight of capital is considerable.
Young people are tired of war and its ideologies.
They have sided with the modern world during their exiles in Iran or Pakistan, they have enjoyed the benefits.
Approximately 65% of the population is under 25 years of age; Kabul now has 5 million inhabitants, one fifth of the total population.
In the cities, government schools are full of girls and boys.
It will be necessary to provide work for those young people who will no longer want to return to the obscurantism of the old parties or the corruption of certain leaders.
All, including armed opponents, are fond of cell phones; television, and its Turkish soap operas that present a modern world, are followed everywhere.
The army is now present.
Will the authorities that will command it be considered legitimate?
Former commanders of the anti-Soviet struggle are already preoccupied with rebuilding provincial militias, which will escape central power.
Afghanistan, a mountainous country with strong local identities, should be able to benefit from some decentralization, in the image of Western nations, but the United States wanted to transform it into a centralized state, with strong presidential power, abolishing the position of Prime Minister that existed since the Constitution of 1964.
President Karzai does not want foreign controls, especially during the elections scheduled for April 2014.
But his country has, since the 1950s and long before, been dependent on foreign aid.
No industry has been restarted, no dams are in good condition, no major irrigation systems are repaired.
Everything is imported; nothing is produced except fruits and vegetables.
Priority is given to private initiative.
In a country ruined by thirty years of war, government control over infrastructure would have been necessary.
There was a rumor that Afghanistan possessed immense mineral wealth.
This only added to the feeling that Westerners were only here to seize it.
Without energy to process iron or copper ore on site, or means of transport to export it through the mountains, there is no mining.
The Chinese have already nearly left the Mes Aynak copper mine, leaving international archaeologists (funded by the World Bank) to search the huge Buddhist site and remain the province’s largest employers.
Afghanistan and Pakistan, which rely heavily on imports and exports, will also have to re-establish normal relations.
The departure of the French fighting troops ended on 20 November.
The new cooperation treaty provides for the continuation of traditional aids: high school for girls, boys, department of French at the university, French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support to the Archaeological Delegation.
Since 2009, in an attempt to "win hearts and minds" and to carry out the impossible task of making aids and offensive actions coincide, a service of "civil-military actions" of the Ministry of Defense (Cimic), abolished in 2012, has led, and has carried out by a small French NGO, many works of collective interest and actions of village agricultural rehabilitation in dozens.
This work, greedy of local labor, could help contain the insurrection: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and increase of arable areas.
What will we leave as a memory, after two billion euros of military spending?
A much more modest budget would contribute to the improvement of local living conditions, which are very harsh in these valleys, which are often more than 2,000 metres above sea level.
The embassy has received dozens of written requests for small agricultural achievements from local communities in Kapisa province.
In order for them to be freed from the insurrection led by foreign groups, which the farmers have told me they wished for, a small, well-controlled and directly affecting civil aid should be maintained in their favour.
A Constitution in force in Egypt
This is another poker move by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, it has decided to play its all.
Taking everyone to court, he announced Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state gave this House an additional two months to complete its work.
Egypt has been relying on a provisional text for almost two years, which has been amended several times, weakening institutional stability and leading to legal imbroglios.
This new initiative has only increased the divide in the country.
For his opponents, the President perseveres in his "autocratic delusion", continuing to "betray his word" and "tread the law".
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible, accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to renounce their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy as protests rage across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote favorably, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Especially since this use of a hasty vote stems from the ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, or I keep the full powers", these are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, overwhelmingly Islamist, voted for the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals missed the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had slammed the door, feeling that they had not been able to assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society had done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 people, replacement members, were added in haste yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, most of the articles were voted unanimously.
Some commentators were amused by the fact that one of the only divergences of the day was expressed around... the time of prayer, with some members of the committee deeming the constituent's pendulum to be ill-adjusted.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, has 234 articles.
Article 2 remains the same as the 1971 Constitution, which states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law."
Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is a major demand, hoped to be able to replace "principles" with "rules", which would have allowed stricter enforcement.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
“Hypocrisy,” replied the Liberals, who saw it as a communication stunt.
Because, according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They include Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying the compliance of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people called to vote are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see the beginnings of a theocracy.”
The fears of the Liberals are further aroused by the fact that the next rector of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
“For the moment, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil status.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not Ulemas but academics, for some trained in the French system" tempers Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "that there may be ambiguity around Article 220, because the terms used borrow from religious vocabulary.
It refers to the "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, ed.].
And the question may in the future arise to what extent civil judges are competent to rule on it.”
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extended powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced in comparison to what they were under the old regime.
Another contentious point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the Defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will trials of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as requested by human rights associations.
They also express their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticidal.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, including the press.
In addition, no article echoes the protection of women, says Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was due to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will march them on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the Center of the World and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the grandeur of biblical truths, modern comfort and wilderness.
Argumenty i Fakty has chosen five main reasons to go to Israel.
Go and adore the holy places
A must-see: the banks of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone who enters these “baptismal funds” will be touched by divine grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of the miracles of Jesus: where the water was turned into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he calmed the storm or where the fishing was miraculous.
This is where Jesus appeared to his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places is in Jerusalem.
Believers walk the Street of Suffering or the Way of the Cross (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the fortress Antonia (the Praetorium), where the trial was held, then leads through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to that of the Stone of the Anointing and the burial.
It is here that the Christian centre of the world stands, a symbol of the salvation of mankind.
According to Christian legend, the monastery of the Cross is erected in the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the most sacred site of the Jews: the Wailing Wall which constitutes the remainder of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC.
According to tradition, people of different confessions leave small words accompanied by prayers that are then answered.
Travel in height
Visit the ruins of Masada Fortress, a former refuge from enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC for his family.
These ruins lie on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can go there on their own.
For the others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m of altitude, is the ski resort of Mont Hermont that welcomes many tourists in winter.
A shuttle can take you from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
The old belief is that pagan gods once inhabited the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country is home to nearly 300 museums.
Unable to visit them all during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth a visit.
First of all: the Israel Museum located near the Knesset (Parliament).
It houses the very ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea manuscripts, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
Also worth seeing is the Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
It exhibits mainly the paintings of the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, the Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of molds of visitors and overseers of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the unique private Ralli Museum where you can admire Rodin's sculptures.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which returns to the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter and enter into total darkness.
Stars are shining.
Then you hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
Israel's three major seaside resorts are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each of them offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, because the temperature of the water does not fall below 21 <0xC2><0xB0> while that of the air can reach 23 <0xC2><0xB0>.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim there all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point on Earth, 417 m below sea level.
The azure water contains brine and very easily retains bathers, even those who do not know how to swim.
The landscapes that surround it are of surreal beauty.
We come to carry out a treatment based on salt water, silt, curative sludge and to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of antiquity
They are guarded by the old city of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris that connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life.
Tourists especially like to walk in the narrow alleys that bear the name of the zodiac signs.
It is said that if you touch the street walls corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile at you.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds who have come to do photo shoots from all over Israel and even from other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll in the Roman theater, "conquer" the fortress of the Crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the principal city of Judea and the residence of Roman procurators, notably Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you are going to Israel, do not worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer dollars to the euro, as they are easily exchanged in shekels (today 1 dollar is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
As for urban transport, these are mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and able to connect the lower and upper parts of the city.
It is almost an underground funicular.
The journey in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, the Jewish tradition is to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport cease their activity.
And the work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, scaleless fish and dishes made up of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts based on coconut milk but also hummus, traditional Jewish pasta, different sauces, balls of ground chickpeas, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats that walk haughtily.
We can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars at night.
These cats love passing places and do not refuse to be given a treat.
Renting a car varies depending on the brand from $37 for 24 hours (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
Entrance to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The Language of Numbers
Three million tourists from around the world visited Israel in 2012.
They were mainly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before visas were cancelled on 9 February 2011.
"Who has a language, in Moscow goes": migrants save money to learn the language
While MPs and human rights activists are debating what the mandatory language test law will give, fraudsters selling “fake” certificates have already made their appearance in the country.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal: to make money to help their families who stayed at home.
Since 1 December, a law has come into force and stipulates that every migrant worker will have to pass a Russian exam.
At the moment, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, over time, the Federal Immigration Service promises, testing will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, the knowledge of the language, but also that of the history of Russia and the foundations of law will have to be validated.
You will need to validate your language knowledge in Russian to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has the status of official language are exempt.
Persons who obtained educational certificates or diplomas before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not affected by this law.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centers will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, the University of Friendship of Peoples, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other higher education institutions of Russia.
Immigrants will be able to take the exams in all cities of the country: more than 160 centers have already been opened throughout the territory.
This initiative to introduce examinations was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law comes into force, human rights defenders have already repeatedly asked the question in the press: what will it do?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First, respond the representatives of the migration service, this will reduce the number of people suffering from "slavery at work".
Many are talking about defending the rights of migrant workers, says the director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan, Victor Sebelev.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
The problems arise for migrants without a profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without an understanding of the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "travel" in an overcrowded house where he and dozens of his fellows will be tormented for months without food and without paper and will have to work between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
“They are promised one thing, and when they arrive, they are cheated, they are taken their passport, and they do not receive the expected salary,” Tolib Charipov, head of the Directorate of Migration Services for the work of Tajikistan’s Migration Service, said in a statement.
Don't argue with me, Officer!
However, many nationals of Central Asian republics who wish to come to Russia for money are confident that they not only know the language of the country they wish to go to, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is of course not their fault, but their misfortune: few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to follow even a fair primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have enough to feed their children without talking about dressing them properly and equipping them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people leave to make money as soon as the opportunity presents itself.
It's hard when you don't know the language, they say.
"You feel diminished and weakened."
Human rights defenders, however, note an important aspect of the language law.
The exams will be intended only for migrants who have legal status.
Without status, there will be no formal examination or work thereafter.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or defense to enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? Administrative barriers and still these language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 rubles.
And then, one can get a fake registration quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have false documents, that we have no record, hence the cases of extortion.
"They are asking us for 100, 200 rubles, what to buy cigarettes, tea," Tajik national Umed Khuchkadamov told reporters.
“Be quick, don’t skimp, and buy yourself a fine work of art.”
From the first day the language law came into force, it was discovered that migrants' registration papers were not the only ones to be forged.
Several false language examination certificates have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
Falsified papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not take them for granted: every migrant who hoped to facilitate the task of examinations had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Power representatives and human rights defenders agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these "paper tips".
The authorities can give migrant workers who have not been able to pass the first-time examination time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes to tighten the law against civilian arms bearers.
Such is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: whether it is the shootings at weddings or the killing organized by the Moscow jurist Dmitry Vinogradov, which killed seven people.
The police want to ban the wearing of rubber bullets in public places and raise the legal age for obtaining a gun licence from 18 to 21 years.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma Committee for Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the Arms Act would be introduced to the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is happy to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "tightening the screw".
An open letter has appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demand to abandon "this insane hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, said Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, over a six-month period in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services while 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded over the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that tightening civil weapons laws will not prevent criminals from sourcing from the black market.
According to them, today in Moscow you can find any weapon for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior says it controls the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factory to officer
The black market for weapons is supplied through several channels.
The main canals are five, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served ten years at the Ministry of Education and Headquarters.
Screenshot taken from a site taking gun commands
The first is the "military trace", i.e. the weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
“These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by the Caucasians,” Baranets said.
The second type of black market weapons are those stolen by criminals from law enforcement.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stockpiles and those stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
Illegal pistols go on sale from military warehouses.
Many of these have often experienced explosions.
“Certified versions indicate that some fires were deliberately set to cover up the deficit,” he said.
For Baranets, the arms manufacturers are for something.
"We see private weapons factories that do not compete with the competition on the international market and sell weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow," said one expert.
One of the other sources of the black market is smuggling.
A significant proportion of guns and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a local production, sometimes artisanal, a mafia has formed and organizes the supply," adds the former military.
Where do the guns come from?
Experts assessed the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on this issue was prepared in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Study for Public Administration.
Specialists analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and Rosstat, criminal records and public data from the weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers explain, come from the military and law enforcement.
Half of the weapons on the black market were found there "due to the fault of employees whose work is related to weapons", the report explains.
According to the researchers, 17% of weapons come from places of military conflict, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture and 5% are from "illegal searches".
An armoury salesman and consultant who has asked to remain anonymous says that for a long time no one has bought the weapons found by these clandestine search specialists; they are too old.
Most often, according to him, sellers will look for the new goods in military warehouses.
The person buys through a sign a unit, for example a TT pistol.
We deliver it to him by passing the goods through a wire mesh.
“He transports it to the city and sells it for €900 per unit with two chargers,” he says.
“It’s true that the police are aware of all the cases, so when crimes are about to be clarified, they make a control purchase from illegal arms dealers,” he added.
"Like in a luxury shop"
The seller and the buyer usually find themselves through knowledge.
I consulted sites, blogs, until a guy showed up and offered to come to Begovaya station where someone would take me to a "corner" to bargain.
The price of the gun was given to me on the spot.
Victor Baranets as Military Observer
In order to find a gun, I have to know someone who has a contact, explains the seller. I know someone, but I don't trust him.
There are sellers in the markets, but there you have to also come saying for example "From such a person, who asked me to convey that his daughter has lost a tooth".
Now I even buy a pair of American fists with the help of a person I trust.
He only gives them to me because he knows I won't give them to him.
Young children are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former militaryman Victor Baranets tried to buy illegal weapons in the mid-1990s as he prepared to publish an article on the subject.
The patterns, he said, have not changed.
