In recent days, a wave of protests has mounted against the low wages practiced by Walmart supermarkets and the famous fast food chains such as McDonald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy's and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
At the moment, no one can predict whether this wave is going to grow or wind down quickly.
These actions are supported by trade unions and a number of left-wing associations.
Alongside the rise in low wages for basic workers at Walmart and fast food chains, protest organizers want to see unions set up.
This sector is not currently covered by the trade union movement.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week after Thanksgiving, the "Black Friday," as a swarming rain of sales gripping millions of people swept across America and sometimes triggered splinters.
That day, some employees of Walmart, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, left their jobs to organize strike pickets with unions and left-wing activists in the company’s stores, whose products are aimed at consumers of the modest and middle classes.
Walmart sells everything from diapers to shotguns to car batteries, vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
Products are on average 8% to 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many low-paid Walmart employees shop only at their workplace.
The price and choice of products have made Walmart one of the most powerful groups in the United States.
According to critics, Walmart can afford to sell its products cheaply due to the low salaries of its employees.
The latter also complain about difficult working conditions, for example the lack of forklifts or portable scanners.
The participants of the "Black Friday" protests demanded a salary increase, they complained that the price of the medical insurance provided by the company had increased from 30 to 100 dollars per month.
For the basic employee at Walmart who earns $9.5 an hour, this is an amount he cannot afford.
Scientists at the California University of Berkley show that if Walmart increased the average salary to $12 an hour, it would cost the group $3.2 billion.
That’s 1.1% more than it currently spends.
If Walmart were to transfer the entire wage increase to consumers, every ride in the store would cost them 46 cents more.
They will spend just $12.39 more in a year than they do now.
Walmart supporters note with satisfaction that the protests took place in only nine states and did no harm to the group.
"Black Friday" continued in stores from 8am in the evening to midnight the next day and Walmart sold over that period 5,000 items per second.
Its cashiers have made a total of 100 million transactions for "Black Friday".
Company spokesman Dan Fogleman said in an interview with the left-wing website Huffington Post that in all "less than five" Walmart employees had left their positions and that the protest was only a "com" operation among many others on the part of the organizing union.
"Next customer!"
