Childbirth in space
The Earth is in danger.
Climate change or collision with a deadly asteroid.
Space shuttle caravans with earthlings on board set out in search of a rescue planet.
To save humanity, a big question arises: how can we continue to make our species live in weightlessness or on a planet of relief?
I don't think there's much choice.
There are actually two real planets that can be conquered, if only by hypothesis.
"This is Venus and Mars," said Vladimir Sourdine, a researcher at the P.K. Chternberg State Astronomical Institute (GAICh).
If conditions on Mars are more suitable for life, the temperature on the surface of Venus is 500 .
We can only live there at very high altitudes or in the orbit of Venus... in space.
We began to focus on the issues of reproduction in space by focusing on the flora.
Half a century ago, we were still experimenting with plants.
Four generations of peas grown in orbit did not differ in any way from terrestrial varieties.
Then, we put in orbit insects, small reproductive Drosophila flies.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to see how a weightless embryo developed.
A completely normal chick is obtained at the exit.
Then the problems begin.
"The problem is related to the fact that the chick has to find support, it has to get on its legs and start moving," explains the director of the laboratory of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences (IMBP) Vladimir Sychev.
When they could not find any support, the chicks were agitated in a disorderly way.
And after 10 hours, the newborns saw their instincts completely atrophy.
The chicks did not react to light or sound.
Unfortunately, they would simply die after four days.
"We rolled their eyes twice, then we gave up, because it's just impossible to work with them there," explains Vladimir Sychev, noting the failure of the experiment with chicks in space.
The last biological "miniature ark" with animals was sent into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, the "Bion" biosatellite will carry only species of the same sex.
There was an experiment with rats sent with their fetus into space.
In principle, nothing supernatural has been discovered.
"It was still about biosatellites, and then it's the only experiment, and we have to do this kind of research," says Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats gave birth to their offspring.
However, it is not yet possible to carry out reproductions directly in space.
It's not a small matter.
By losing their usual environment, animals are no longer able to realize their sexual instincts.
Unlike animals, humans are capable of this in principle.
Homo sapiens possesses abstract thought, it is able to create a suitable emotional background.
This type of experiment is not carried out for ethical reasons.
But women have been in space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was taken by Terechkova.
And the female organism is what humanity has most precious.
Our gull flew away and no one on Earth could tell if it would stand after a space flight.
If she could have given birth to a child after the flight.
“No one answered that question,” said Vakhtang Vatchnadze, a retired rocket and space worker.
In June 1964, just one year after her flight into space, the first woman cosmonaut Valentina Terechkova gave birth to a little girl.
The father of the child, Andrian Nikolayev was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman cosmonaut Svetlana Savitskaya, after being twice in orbit and even working in an extra-vehicular environment, gave birth to a son.
However, the risk persists.
We have few, even very few cosmonauts who have had nothing and who give birth to healthy offspring after long flights.
"And if they are longer, it presents a danger even during orbital flights," concludes the pilot and cosmonaut, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of Russia, Valeriy Poliakov.
Yet humanity must seek new solutions in biotechnology, radiation protection and the creation of artificial gravity.
Hydrology laboratory of the Cosmonaut Preparation Centre: mandatory stage of flight preparation.
Here, in zero buoyancy, cosmonauts train for extra-vehicular exits.
Water mimics weightlessness.
If for adults, water is comfortable but yet a foreign environment, for infants, it is their real element.
Small amphibious men seem to confirm this: life on Earth comes from the ocean.
To the extent that the baby evolves about 9 months in the lymphatic fluid of his mother's belly, it is easier for him to then get used to the water.
This is in principle logical, because from his birth until his first bath, it only happens 2 weeks.
“It’s very little to forget,” explains infant swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
In a word, if for the child who has just been born weightlessness is a more natural state, the woman needs gravity, a force of weight.
In weightlessness, the muscles of the belly, pelvis atrophy very quickly, the baby's ability to push is lost.
All right, let's ignore that by relying on birth simulators.
Of course one can prepare a delivery in a special room, the woman will manage to get it out.
"And then?" asks Valeriy Poliakov to invite reflection on this complex issue.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravitation.
If it does not feel the attraction of the earth, the body does not form the skeleton or the muscular system.
One cannot dress an infant like an adult with a special training suit.
He will simply be deprived of his vital needs.
"And this experiment that we would consider in this case by imagining the birth of a child in a foreign environment will lead to the return to Earth of a disabled child, completely misfit," said Igor Pestov, Director of the Bioethics Committee of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
The birth of children in space is still a matter of theory.
However, over time this will become a reality, when the Earthlings will travel in their shuttles to a distant planet that will become the habitat of their spaceborn offspring.
