Do you therefore consider the adoption of this law rather as an advantage or as an additional burden for the administration?
I believe that this law is a step in the right direction and I hope that the future will confirm it.
The problem that can arise is that these rules become more stringent and that it is not possible to comply with them.
Already under the previous regulatory regime, the claimant (e.g. the regional council, in the case of regional operational programs) forced the controlled subjects to accept that any breach of the market law meant a breach of budgetary discipline.
Is it really helpful to make the law more stringent in this way?
No, not that way, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack the system or abuse it, but not punish those who make formal mistakes without affecting the decision-making process.
Such a system will put more pressure on the administration.
So what is the solution to get out of it?
Let's look where we're not going.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the SDG is not going to bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called <0xC5><0xA0>varc system - what does it mean?
Is the <0xC5><0xA0>varc system prohibited or authorized?
The law must be enforced in one way or another, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government cannot prevent an authority from going to inspect and demanding compliance with the law.
He may declare, "We will change the law and authorize it," but he cannot say that we will act as if nothing was wrong.
The Law on Contracts contains relatively strict rules on the formalities to be performed, precisely in order to protect the call for tenders.
But it is also tragic that a bidder is eliminated solely because of formal defects.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be fair and that is, in my opinion, what is lacking in us.
