Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this agency, it is the second member state of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started a close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and in the following years participated in a number of ESA projects.
Poland's journey to space, however, began much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, passionate Poles were working on space flights; they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld's lecture at the Astronomical Observatory in Warsaw on December 6, 1933, in which he presented ideas drawn from his avant-garde work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold and years later <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his work "Introduction to Astronautics".
Doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books on this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a world-renowned propagator of astronautics, his contribution was notably rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the far side of the Moon.
In 1925 a rocket engine was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket was to be used to propel or brake the draisine.
The only information known about this draisine is that of the press of the time.
From 1933, Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by the Kom<0xC3><0xB3>rka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
The records show that this research had reached the testing stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search stopped.
In 1937, the plans of a photoelectric fighter rocket, drawn by the engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski, appeared in the specialized press and the following year the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" was published by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects using the rocket technique were led by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee had been established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other aeronautical works were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, a company is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal Probl<0xC3><0xA8>me, in which there are four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
In early 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to join the International Astronautical Federation (established in 1951) and by the fall, the PTA had become a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902–1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters was 80 cm long and weighed just under 5 kg.
Later an improved version, RM-1A, was built, and in the summer of 1959 flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket began in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket was 1.4 meters long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962-1965 succeeded the first RM-type rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a volume of 0.4 litres, while the Meteor-1B had a volume of 0.34 litres and the Meteor-1C had a volume of 0.62 litres.
The maximum range of all these types of craft was 37 km.
In the period 1965-1968, Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Later versions of the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is still worth mentioning the entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladim<0xC3><0xAD>r Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
Repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Works Act.
This decision has sparked a lively public debate.
It is undoubtedly interesting to look at this issue from a broader perspective.
Economic systems oriented towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This means that the different economic entities as well as the national economic systems are constantly in conflict with each other.
This results from the principle of free trade and free (unlimited) movement of private capital allied with unbridled financial speculation.
The considerable differences in the price of labour (wages) generate a tension on prices.
It is necessary to put the following meaning under this term: a producer strives by importing low-sold goods to resist economic competition by "making" the price of the competitor more expensive, with the aim of removing a greater share of the market and thus increasing his own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either moving production abroad, buying at low prices, or disappearing, the result being significant unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment it generates, the social burdens of the state necessarily increase.
All this situation intensifies the perfect unwillingness of gentlemen entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus to compensate for the economic and social damage caused to the whole of society by this race for profit.
This situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create in the different economies a situation in which the governments of the different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to them.
In other words, governments put their own people at the mercy of private capital without taking into account social collapse.
This is manifested mainly in the amendments of the laws in force.
The objective is to economically force its own population to accept the dictate of private capital prices, especially in the field of wages.
This is due on the one hand to a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and on the other hand to the restriction of the rights of employees in the field of labour legislation.
The result is growing poverty and deepening differences between the rich and the poor.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, there have been public food distribution points for the poor who cannot provide for themselves with their own work.
The number of these people is already in the millions.
In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it becomes quite common for wage earners to receive such wages that the state is forced to pay an extra fee so that they reach the vital minimum.
For example, such a scandal has been updated in the case of employees working as auxiliaries in the federal parliament.
The economic measures of virtually all southern EU member states undoubtedly generate a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century), or to live with poverty wages, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day their private capital will be invested in their country.
The question here is: where will this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will pass from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turkish, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European salary.
This also applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media say, tirelessly, that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the led economy leads to an economic catastrophe.
Private capital strongly defends the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
It is therefore necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence, and even direct, politics today, according to its own selfish interests, and by the same token, the whole state.
The answer to that question is undoubtedly yes.
The proof of this is that there is an almost all-powerful lobby present in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifesting itself in the field of corruption, through the granting of mutual benefits, in legislation, where everything is reprehensible but not punishable.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, the situation is such that due to the lack of financial resources, the national ministries delegate the drafting of laws to law firms closely related to industry.
These bills are then passed in the Bundestag.
The totality of power does not come from the people, as Western-type constitutions declare, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is clear that liberal-oriented democracies are now quickly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled "The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Time of Caesar and Pompey": "The State was long in decline and functions were assigned by violence.
Bribes, illegally obtained favors, and stones and swords were also used to obtain these positions.
The under-the-table and the corruption proliferated without limits and the people went to the elections with already sold voices" ... ... "The honest people did not seek at all to obtain positions, it resulted once the state was transformed 8 months without consuls".... ' We really began to say that the remedy to this difficult situation was an autocracy, but that it was necessary to choose a man with energy "
In conclusion, as in antiquity, present-day society is based on the preference for personal profit, without regard for the interest of society as a whole.
In its essence, private capital is no longer capable of understanding and asserting the interests of society as a whole.
The result, today as in the past, is an unprecedented decadence of elites, without any effort to carry out in-depth reforms.
We must therefore look for the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
In the current state of affairs, the disappearance of these systems in favour of liberal democracies can be seen as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that today’s elites are completely unaware of the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future loss of life, the humanitarian and social crises we are witnessing today, and the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history.
Repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long run.
Under the pressure of economic competition, both at the international level and at the internal European level, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is systemic.
The solution consists of reforms with socio-political aims, which will strengthen investments in state capital in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
