The architects of the MVRDV firm prove that true adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To be convinced, just look at Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it's very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the lower side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist at a large nearby company, tells us: "Yes, this building is indeed beautiful."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has internet, an iPad and e-books.
Today, no one goes willingly to one of these nerdy libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town that has nothing appealing at the gates of Rotterdam, holds a rather special record.
The municipality of 80,000 people has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to give back a few neurons to the brains, the city decided a few years ago to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictional bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of pretty little miniatures in painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to regain control of the statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architectural office MVRDV, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of witty and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and entered the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the members of the jury were still looking at each other, baffled and shrugging, Maas, the cheeky, piled up his books of choice in order of size to make it a pyramid, and ended his speech supported by activist arguments with one: "Common dear!"
Here she is, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30-million-euro mountain sprang from the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and some buildings and semi-detached houses for a total of 50 dwellings.
In early November, the mountain of books received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, this dull little village, which until today had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and a town hall of a mind-boggling ugliness, whose white facades invite one to think that they are home to a dairy, has been enriched with a contemporary architectural work.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Road to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
True, an elevator transports you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open to you when you walk on the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior entirely made of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and the elegant street lights speak unequivocally the language of municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking for public benches, dogs and little boys and girls playing ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally, the library shelves are along the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Willy Maas.
We have completely disrupted the classic spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain of books has been skillfully arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black shelves of the library, which are sometimes paneling, sometimes balustrades, sometimes staircases.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even the architects and engineers of the hardened building do not want unknown materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” says Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found in a Frisian farm an ad hoc waste from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, synthetic membranes of one millimeter thickness have been used for years as substrates in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and you save time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates with a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and transforms into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, whose smell evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
After almost 500 meters, the literary café offers us a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and ficus in pots.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to maintaining the ideal level of humidity of the literary mountain air.
Gifts for the New Soul
“It’s amazing, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology,” Trouborst says.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is under a glass bell, the sun illuminates the interior only for a short time, even on sunny days.
The thick wooden beams mounted across the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade serve as a sunshade, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
Fully automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic computer scientist, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "at last found soul".
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, each citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure filled the gaps in the library that was not yet fully filled (today it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing from all sides.
For architect Winy Maas, "there is nothing worse than a half-empty library."
“I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between each citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration."
This is how MVRDV achieved the master discipline that is called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new page in literary history.
Although she may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
