"Marketing protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well-known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys such protection that the company bearing its name cannot lodge a complaint.
And even if she could, she's not sure she'd win.
“It’s becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at the firm Taylor Wessing, which specializes in infringing property rights in the Far East.
Every week, a new file arrives on my desk.
Imitators only need a few extra letters to register their marks.
Thus, instead of Gucci, we record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we record Prada-Kny.
German companies are also being legally copied, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sports goods.
Pattloch opens a folder containing the registrations made with the Beijing Trademark Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company filed the trademark Zegna DF Puma, a name that the firm artificially created by appropriating part of the name of Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a known fact that the Chinese have become the world champions of copying and infringement of intellectual property.
In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping malls that sell virtually only counterfeits.
However, Pattloch’s cases are different: his constituents task him with tackling the fact that the Chinese Trademark Office officially confers on Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese speak of "Bang Mingpai", a related brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
It is with this term that women who marry rich men are designated.
The Chinese authorities say they have nothing to blame.
"It's bad for business, we have to fight this trend," Pattloch demands.
"The brand is sweetened, the singularity disappears, the damage to reputation is enormous."
Financial losses and legal costs amount to millions for the sectors concerned, especially for costly flagship products.
According to data from market analysis company CLSA, China represents, with an annual volume of 15 billion euros, the world's third largest and fastest growing luxury goods market.
However, it is not easy to remove dubious registrations from the trademark registry and these procedures are expensive.
These can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch refers to the trials in which the court dismissed the complaint, because after a long period of time, the name criticized had become a "market reality".
Pattloch explains that if the complainant is unlucky, he may even be forced to pay money to the plagiarist, because he would have harmed his brand in China.
In this area, it is sometimes the law of the jungle that dominates.
Famous cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle against construction machine builder Sany, the same company that had just bought concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
This is why the Chinese can use an emblem that resembles the Mercedes star.
Geely, Volvo's acquirer, used a blue and white logo reminiscent of BMW's. The dispute was settled and Geely had to change it.
The fashion house Lacoste had lost against plagiarists in Hong Kong and Singapore who had reoriented the gaze of the famous crocodile in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing admits, however, that it experienced some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, the office reportedly moved last year from an “emergency situation in the course of work to a restored normality”.
Thus, the number of unprocessed opposition proceedings would have fallen by 22 per cent.
Nearly 57,000 cases of this type would have been closed, which represents an increase of 75% compared to the previous year.
However, 81,500 cases remain outstanding at the Office.
Acting is expensive
As is often the case in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
According to the office, this is a record and it means that China is for the tenth time in a row at the top of the ranking for the number of new deposits in the world.
This would also apply to the total number of legal trademarks, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the Office reportedly had 1.8 billion yuan in registration fees.
In other words, each record earned an average of 1,280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs much more, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg illustrates.
For more than seven years, the company has been battling a Chinese plagiarist.
Certainly, the Germans were able to get the illegal manufacture of vehicle components suspended.
However, the impersonator was able to maintain his Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
“It’s our fault, because surnames cannot be protected in Germany,” says Hanno Wentzler, CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The Trademark Office therefore rejected the objection of the Munichers.
Freudenberg certainly won in the next two instances, but the opposing party continues to fight to this day.
Vigilance is required
Today, the case is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, believes in a positive outcome of the trial and boasts the professionalism of the judges.
Nevertheless, he adds, "the procedure is long, challenging and costs us a lot of time and money."
Internal costs are also difficult to assess, and the archives department has even had to review the records of the past 100 years to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg even offered the opposing party a “big six-figure euro sum” to settle the dispute in vain.
“This is what we see what it means for us,” Wentzler says.
The dangers of the Far East threaten even to spill over to Europe.
This would be the case if imitators from this region ensured the exploitation of unprotected trademarks.
For example, a Chinese producer wanted to file the name Freudenberg in Germany for a shoe and leather company.
The company had long since abandoned this sector, but it had still been able to prevent the deposit.
Wentzler added: "Vigilance is required."
Pattloch and he advise German companies to exercise great caution in their trade relations with China.
It is not enough, according to them, to rely on international trademark law, foreigners should rather "register in China everything that is likely to be protected", as Wentzler says.
Otherwise, the costs can be much higher than those of registration.
Indeed, if Freudenberg lost the battle in the last act of his legal drama, the company would have to pay licensing fees to the opposing party for the use of its own name, as Wentzler explains.
Otherwise, we would lose our place in the segment of the market in question.
