It is Monday evening, the Imbongi choir repeats a new song in the music room of the Institute of Medical Psychology in Heidelberg.
Fifty singers between the ages of 23 and 69 came from the geneticist in human medicine to the man at home.
"Om'Obani" is not an easy piece, each chorister has different lyrics, all in a very exotic language: Zulu, a language spoken by 11 million people in South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique and parts of Swaziland.
Be Helped to Help Yourself
UNAIDS, the United Nations AIDS Programme, estimates that 34 million people worldwide are affected by the disease.
23.5 million of them live in South Africa.
Swaziland has 245,000 people infected.
In addition, more than 40% of the population is HIV-positive.
180 AIDS orphans from the village of Esitjeni have found sponsors in Germany thanks to the association "Voices for Africa".
70 of them attend a secondary school.
