We need to make the transition.
"And this success is my responsibility to the people and to God," he told state television.
His speech was intended for the entire people, but also especially for Christian Copts, liberals, enlightened Muslims and lay people.
For all members of the confused and desperately disunited opposition are afraid.
They are afraid of a theocracy on the Nile at the hands of the powerful Muslim Brotherhood.
Mohamed Morsi said, almost apologizing, that he had temporarily restricted the powers of the Constitutional Court and expanded his own "in order to save the revolution".
However, the Egyptians and the world don’t really know what this 61-year-old engineer, who holds a doctorate from the American University of Southern California, wants to save.
Will the judiciary be overthrown?
The 234 articles hastily drafted by the 100-person majority Islamic constituent assembly during a 15-hour night force tour are indeed worrying to some extent.
As in previous constitutions, the draft provides that jurisprudence is based on "principles of Islamic law".
But what does the word "principles" really mean?
This was and still is a question of interpretation, and there is good reason to fear that Islamists will use the vague formulation and the resulting legal leeway to apply a stricter interpretation of Sharia.
In any case, this suggests a newly introduced article stating that, with regard to all matters related to Sharia, al-Azhar University should be consulted. The institution is the most important Islamic institution in the country and its brilliance radiates throughout the Sunni Islamic world.
This may, but does not necessarily mean that the clergy will monitor the legislative apparatus, which would de facto result in the judicial power being placed under guardianship.
Many points of the draft Constitution are subject to interpretation.
Another problematic aspect is the probable maintenance of military jurisdiction.
During Mubarak's reign, these courts worked to suppress opponents.
After the fall of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were held by the military.
The state must also protect “the true nature of the Egyptian family” and “promote its morals and values.”
From a legal point of view, the wording is so vague that state institutions could even control the content of cinematographic art and literature.
In other words, it would simply be censorship.
Moreover, no article expressly guarantees equality between men and women.
Instead, another article forbids offending or defaming the Prophet Muhammad or his envoys.
However, the article does not define what an offense is or how it should be punished.
Equally dubious is the wording implying that it is forbidden to "offend people".
Is it enough to draw a caricature of the president or to tell a joke at the expense of a lawyer?
Many points are therefore subject to interpretation in the draft that Morsi submits to the vote and which, in his own words, will "very soon" be the subject of a referendum with the Egyptians.
"The Revolution is Reborn"
The opposition has been mobilizing for weeks against the numerical superiority of Islamists.
On Friday night, tens of thousands of protesters gathered in an unusual concord on Cairo’s Tahrir Square, promising to bring down sharia law before it takes effect.
“The revolution is reborn and we are going to win,” said Hamdin Sabbahi, who came third in the presidential election.
Nobel Peace Prize winner and former head of the International Atomic Energy Agency Mohamed El Baradei said the draft constitution is "to be thrown into the trash of history".
On Twitter, the instant messaging service, he accused Morsi’s supporters of wanting to foment a “putsch against democracy.”
"If he proclaims the referendum, we will go to his palace and overthrow him," said Jasser Said, an opponent.
“We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers is not yet atoned for,” said Khaled Ali, a politician and member of the opposition, according to Egyptian media.
In addition, several judges have announced that they do not want to monitor the referendum, which would result in its nullity.
“The Qur’an is our Constitution.”
For its part, the well-organized Muslim Brotherhood called for a counter-demonstration not on Tahrir Square as a precautionary measure, but on the other bank of the Nile, where a great prayer was organized in front of the University of Cairo.
The veiled women and supporters of the Salafists, who participated in large numbers, chanted: "The people demand the application of the law of God."
“Clean up our country!” they asked Morsi, claiming that “the Qur’an [was] their Constitution.”
A struggle for sovereignty over the symbolic Tharir Square, where everything began, would soon have created a situation similar to that of a civil war.
Obviously, this is what Morsi’s supporters wanted to avoid.
The Muslim Brotherhood said that opponents of the draft constitution, as well as its supporters, spoke loudly.
According to them, it is now time to let the people decide through the ballot box the direction the country should take.
The project of the Islamists will certainly win the majority.
"Human rights are not mentioned once"
Hafez Abu Saeda is angry at this imposed constitutional process which should have lasted until February and encompassed all social forces.
This 48-year-old human rights lawyer and president of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EOHR) had defended the Muslim Brotherhood when they were in prison or in court under Mubarak.
He did so not because he shared their conception of the world, but because for him human rights are indivisible.
That is why he was beaten, tried and imprisoned.
"And now, the term is not even pronounced once in the new constitution," he said during his interview with the Welt am Sonntag.
The extension of Morsi's powers to the three powers discouraged the lawyer.
These measures are blatant violations of the rules of democracy and will create a new dictatorship in Egypt.
"Instead of strengthening civil society, the president de facto strips him of all his powers," Saeda said.
Yet a democracy cannot function without civil society organisations.
Saeda feels neglected, including by the international community, which looks at the battle between the different political ideologies on the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and nervousness.
That could pay off.
A protester in Tharir Square warns: "You are giving birth to a monster that you will no longer be able to control."
Norway's rakfisk: Is it the most fragrant fish in the world?
The five million people who live in Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe, but also in the world.
Could the secret of the country’s success be linked to the locals’ appetite for an extremely fragrant fish?
Take some advanced cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of wet and dirty football clothing.
Wait a week.
And you get the disturbing smell of rakfisk, one of Norway’s most popular dishes.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about 3 hours from Oslo.
It snows, the landscape is spectacular - and this smell, ubiquitous, permeates the air.
The rakfisk consists of trout sprinkled with salt and fermented in water for a duration - depending on the smell you want it to exhale - which can go up to a year.
When darkness sets in and it’s cold, Norwegians gather en masse to attend a festival that takes place here, in Fagernes, dedicated to this incredible culinary specialty.
"You eat raw, then you swallow a glass of aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, a local full-time firefighter who is also called "Rakfisk General", who is in charge of managing the festival.
Around us, people swallow small pieces of fish and put on a large amount of drink.
“Some people prefer aquavit to rakfisk,” adds Havard.
Drinking kills the smell.
I'm trying a few pieces.
If you can avoid getting it under your nose, it's not bad - it sounds like a sushi that would have spent long hours on a bus.
The rakfisk dates back to a time when Norway was poor, before the invention of refrigeration, the fish was immersed in airtight water barrels, then salted in autumn.
Then, during the winter, once well fermented, the fish came out and - no doubt with the senses lessened by alcohol - ate.
In the previous generation, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country to find work, emigrating mainly to the United States.
Now the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by full employment, high wages and a comprehensive health care system.
The Swedes, their old rivals whose country was not so long ago richer than Norway, cross the border to come to work.
The rakfisk is considered something important, a vital, though fragrant, element of Norway's past.
This is one of the most expensive dishes.
But everything is expensive - a pint of beer or a sandwich will cost you 10 € each.
Norway does not often make mention of it in international news, which is not to his displeasure.
Here, people are unwilling to talk about Anders Breivik, the right-wing extremist racist who shot 77 people, including women and children.
When they talk about this killing, they talk about the “July 22 incident.”
Norwegians find it difficult to accept that in their peaceful country, one of their own may have committed such an act of barbarism.
Since the early 1970s, Norway owes its wealth to its oil and gas industry, one of the largest in the world.
“But oil is not the only reason for our success,” says Anna, our waitress, with blond hair and a piercing blue eye, the image of Nordic well-being, with a plate of rakfisk in her hand.
We are, as you say, prudent people.
His English, like most people who live here, is perfect.
We are discreet, we do not like to be noticed.
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution - everything, with the exception of a small percentage of money from this industry, is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When other countries were throwing money out the window, in the years leading up to the international financial crisis, Norway was able to keep its purse strings tight.
“As long as you can ski in winter and hike in summer, we are happy,” says Anna.
"Not to mention the rakfisk," she adds in a carefree laugh.
I stand in the snow and queue to buy food - I got my dose of rakfisk.
On the menu, a hamburger made of momentum, a real discovery, it is excellent.
But tonight, the smell of fish is everywhere.
The hotel I'm staying at is one of many places where rakfisk is served for dinner and where you can vote for the best of them - or perhaps the most fragrant of them.
There is a TV show where the presenter wears a bow tie, surrounded by rakfisk plates.
It looks like the Eurovision contest.
"What score did you give to the best fish in the Thor-Juergen Mountains?"
"Here's the points, Havard."
We hear laughter and applause.
A man falls from his chair, perhaps because of the abuse of aquavit.
Or maybe it's because of the fish fumes.
Mexican Enrique Pena Nieto has a tough start.
As incoming President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office in Mexico, Will Grant of the BBC is interested in the difficulties that await him and the expectations of the people, which are many.
Road traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad at the moment.
In a city where traffic jams are legion in normal times, a security dam has been put in place since Monday, blocking several key road accesses in the capital and causing real chaos on the roads.
Nevertheless, the aim was not to prevent people from going to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching Parliament.
Next Saturday, the new president of Mexico, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential scarf to become the new president at the head of the nation.
A complicated task awaits him.
Mexico’s economy is doing well, from the results that we owe to the outgoing president Felipe Calderon, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already cost the lives of about 60,000 people in six years.
“My government has made a commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence,” Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Before joining the U.S. President, Mr. Pena Nieto was governor of the state of Mexico.
A very populated and sprawling state that encloses the capital. In its land of choice, the opinions regarding this new leader are divided.
A direct man
In the bucolic municipality of Valle del Bravo, for example, it is inscribed in the memory of all.
The premises attribute to him the development of tourism and infrastructure in the municipality.
To reach the city you can take one of the new highways of M Pena Nieto, a significant improvement has been made to these roads, once bumped and full of cracks.
Plaques bearing his name hang outside a new sports complex and an impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
"We are counting on him to bring about lasting change," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a congressman and party member of Mr Pena Nieto, the PRI.
In terms of security and economics in particular, we hope for a real change that our country so badly needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was ousted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years spent outside the Los Pinos presidential palace, there are many expectations within the party about Enrique Pena Nieto.
He rejects criticism from opponents who blame the new president for lacking charisma.
He is a whole man, very committed, with an excellent vision of the country.
He is an excellent statesman and, above all, he knows how to listen.
However, this is not always the image the people have of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast with the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be more blatant.
Hidden under the highways, it is, in many ways, a suburb of Mexico City.
And the problems in the municipality are also concrete and urban.
Earlier this year, the military was called to the rescue to fight drug gangs in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is particularly serious.
In a disaster area, the bodies of dozens of women murdered in the past two years have been found on the edge of landfill.
More than 1,000 women were killed in the state of Mexico while Mr. Pena Nieto was governor, a rate far higher than in the very violent city of Ciudad Juarez – a place infamous for the number of innocent women killed there.
Critics of Mr. Pena Nieto say that at best he failed to stem the problem of murders committed against women when he was in office.
At worst, they accuse his administration of refusing to face reality.
In a concrete house, typical of this dilapidated neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles to hold back her tears when she shows me pictures of her deceased daughter, Mariana Luna.
The official version reports a suicide committed by Mariana in 2010.
However, her family thinks she was killed by her partner.
“When I arrived at her house, it seemed to me that her body had been washed,” says Se<0xC3><0xB1>ora Buendia.
Signs indicated that she had been beaten, and the cadaveric rigidity had already begun.
While her mother tells the story, a photo of Mariana dresses the wall, next to a cross with the word: Justice.
However, this is exactly what the family was denied.
The authorities treated me as if I were an old cunt, a troublemaker, a whiner.
They want us to accept what they say and shut up.
“But it is not normal that there are so many irregularities and omissions,” she said.
When President Pena Nieto receives his scarf on Saturday, it will be accompanied by a heavy responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by crime in Mexico over the past six years and the new president has vowed to make it his priority during his tenure.
"I hope he will be as good as he was when he was governor," Congressman Olvera said in Valle del Bravo.
However, this is exactly what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear the most.
Bradley Manning has not complained of ill-treatment, prosecutors say.
Prosecutors are trying to counter claims of ill-treatment that Bradley Manning allegedly suffered during his detention.
The trial is about Manning’s detention in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants to file the case on the grounds that Manning's abduction took place under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to show on Friday that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of causing the largest leak of classified information in the history of the U.S. military -- has missed numerous opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he claims to have suffered during his military detention.
During a cross-examination with Manning during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney General Maj. Ashden Fein said that recordings of weekly visits to Manning by officers during his nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, did not reveal any complaints about his treatment.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defence filed a motion demanding that the Manning case be dismissed on the grounds that the abduction took place under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place one day after Manning testified of his desire to commit suicide during his detention.
This military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At the hearing on Friday, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms the officers had filled out after their meeting with Manning, during his detention in Quantico Military Prison, where he was subjected to maximum solitary confinement from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein referred to the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment he received from his guards was "excellent" and that the treatment he had received in prison was "overall very professional."
The forms do not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed orally concerns about certain issues and that visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would take care of them, but they did not record the issues raised.
“They wrote ‘no problems’ (after addressing the concerns), and yet that didn’t mean I hadn’t raised any issues,” Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment during a January 2011 interview with the special commission that had met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during the meeting was to have his restrictive status changed to indicate a “risk of injury.”
The military said it had assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for suicide risk -- for his protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know that I was okay, and I wanted to be removed from this status ... in order to benefit from a better quality of life from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the Marine Corps Base Military Prison in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he planned to commit suicide while in Kuwait and fainted once because of the heat.
He added that not being kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was happening in the rest of the world was very distressing.
“My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage,” Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was gonna die in that cage.
Once in Quantico, Manning said he had spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only items he had were a mattress, blanket, flip-flops, clothing and his glasses.
He tried to stay in motion, because sleeping or lying down during the day was against the rules.
Manning also pointed out that when he was trying to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him so that they could see his face.
Manning’s lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning’s treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation reported in his testimony Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked for an entire night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other detainees one morning during the call.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover himself with a blanket during the call.
During the judge’s questions Friday, Manning said he had deduced from his guard’s order that he must release his cover that could have hidden his nudity, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to release it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before, as he allegedly tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reportedly told the officer that he could have used the rubber band on his underpants or flip-flops to injure himself, but he hadn't.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, flip-flops, and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account his experiences during his detention and that he will significantly reduce his sentence should he be found guilty in a court-martial, a trial that is expected to be held early next year.
The defense said Manning plans to plead guilty to the less serious offenses and fight for the abandonment of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend, with prosecutors expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has confirmed that Manning was incarcerated in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention of all detainees in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include the theft of public property or documents, collusion with the enemy, resulting in the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of information related to national defense.
If all charges are upheld, he will be sentenced to life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American identity crisis
He says many were forced to leave Mexico because of lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame those who left; they remind Mexicans of difficult times, he said.
Navarrette says Mexican Americans find themselves caught between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, arriving in the lobby, in front of customs and immigration services, I felt lost.
Signs indicated two paths: one for the "Mexicans" ("Mexicans"), another for the "Extranjeros" ("Foreigners").
I stood still for several seconds, not knowing which way to go.
I grew up in central California, where I've been called the "Mexican" all my life.
It’s an ethnic qualifier, just like the one my friends in Boston use when they call themselves “Irish,” or my friends in New York when they call themselves “Italian.”
Then I became a Mexican-American.
But here it was Mexico.
And, on the land where my grandfather was born, there is no need for a special qualification or a bond.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, well enough to handle an interview in one or the other language.
But I don't have the vocabulary of an aboriginal, and I can't lose my American accent.
So I took my U.S. passport and headed to the "Foreigners" line.
I thought about that time of the week when the new Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited President Obama at the White House.
Generally, when the leaders of these two countries meet, their preferred themes are immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto also wanted to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one of the reasons why Mexicans stay in Mexico rather than risk it in the United States.
He wants to ally himself with the United States and Canada, and create a Union for Trade on the model of the European Union, but in North America.
And Pena Nieto pledges to continue the war against the drug cartels in Mexico, although he did not provide further details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and filled with bitterness.
Most Americans probably never thought about the fact that in 1848, the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to cede in writing half of their territory to the tip of the rifle.
But for Mexicans, who think in terms of centuries, and not minutes, memories are everywhere.
Therefore, as soon as a U.S. official makes any criticism of Mexico, you begin to hear -- in the Mexican press, and among the elites -- complaints about how the Americans are undermining their neighbor's sovereignty.
And Montezuma's kids are looking for a fight.
And yet, for Mexico, the most difficult relationship is the one that the country has with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans who live in the United States.
Do you want to talk about bitterness?
There's a lot of them.
Mexico has its winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities and others for whom the country does not offer them.
The only reason for the large number of Mexican ancestors in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that at some point in our family tree, a person, perhaps a parent or grandparent, found no opportunity in Mexico and had to go to the North.
And more often than not, this person matched a typical profile -- dark, uneducated skin from a poor village, etc.
We are their descendants, and we are loyal to them.
Not Mexico.
And even if we are living the American dream right now, we have gone to good schools and we have good situations, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream we are living, not the Mexican dream.
Our identity is sometimes disturbed, but our loyalty is obvious.
We give it to the United States.
On the other hand, we know that a part of the Mexican elite among the ruling class does not like us.
The feeling is reciprocated.
We remind them of a humiliating defeat and they cough up us as if we were individuals of inferior strain and not sufficiently Mexican.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
For them, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families had not failed when they lived in Mexico, they would never have left.
And we would not find ourselves stuck on the right side of the fence, living comfortably in the United States, but as lost souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and who immigrated legally to the United States as a child, reminds me that there are frictions between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans, as Mexicans more firmly claim their identity and Mexican-Americans are upset.
Although she is a U.S. citizen, she feels like she is part of two countries.
Moreover, many Mexican-Americans I know don’t feel like they’re part of one country or the other.
We love the music of the Mexican band, Los Tigres del Norte, but also that of Bruce Springsteen.
We have the best of both worlds, but we are not rooted in either.
In Mexico, we are considered Americans.
And in the United States, we are considered Mexicans.
And now, to complicate the relationship a little more, as I learned during my stay, some Mexican leaders and some of the intelligentsia want to get closer to the Diaspora.
They want the Mexican-Americans to work as fortune ambassadors for Mexico, representing its interests in the United States.
We will have to explain to our American compatriots that Mexico is a superb country that must be visited and put pressure on political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yes, of course.
That won't happen.
There's too much bitterness.
And, given the pervasive wage inequalities, corruption and drug-related violence, many of us are not convinced that this is a fantastic country.
You're gonna have to deal with this on your own, amigos.
That's normal.
While some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States for the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, they must therefore accept that some Mexican-Americans still like the way their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexicans" than I thought we were.
Old quarrels, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas is yet another failure for peace.
Can there ever be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed seems to indicate that such a hope is in vain.
While the same futile arguments for who started persist, dozens of buildings have been reduced to dust; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; and, for the first time, rockets fired from Gaza have landed near Tel Aviv, the metropolis of Israel, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But while the Israelis and Palestinians seem stuck in their former conflict, all around them, the Middle East is in full swing.
The Arab Spring has shattered everything, and whether we like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis are caught up in this regional upheaval.
Perhaps their struggle will intensify a little more.
Yet there is every reason to believe that this could help them out of this deadly deadlock.
A war that makes no losers or winners
At first glance, it seems difficult to be optimistic.
Even though the ceasefire granted on 21 November continues, this week’s fighting has bolstered supporters of the force on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has run Gaza since 2007, will brag about forcing Israelis to give up, even though Gaza has suffered a beating.
Having killed some of its leaders and pushed Gaza’s 1.7 million people back into one of the world’s most miserable and overcrowded corners, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently in the hands of their rivals Fatah, the other more moderate Palestinian faction.
In addition, Hamas leaders might say that time is their ally.
The influence of Islamists in the Arab world is growing, and Hamas has made rich and powerful friends.
Turkey, a burgeoning regional power, once Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has taken a stand for Hamas; as has Qatar, one of the Gulf’s wealthiest and most dynamic states.
Hamas members rejoice and say that the Islamist crescent is curving around Israel, from Lebanon in the north, where the Hezbollah militia exercises its dominance, to Syria, where Islamist-leaning rebels can overthrow Bashar El Assad, and to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And most importantly, on the southern flank of Israel, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under the presidency of Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and central of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time to devote to Hamas.
On the other hand, the Muslim Brotherhood are cousins of Hamas, and their leaders more easily rely on public opinion.
In future diplomacy, Hamas can emerge as an important player that can no longer be excluded even by Israel and America.
Meanwhile, Israel’s hardline supporters will draw the opposite conclusions.
In military terms, Hamas has been put back in the box.
The missile interception system called Iron Dome has proven its effectiveness and many Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
Israelis will be able to sleep on both ears - for a while.
In terms of diplomacy, America is renewing its unwavering support; and many European countries have accused Hamas of being the source of the latest wave of violence.
But above all, Israel prospered, especially under Binyamin Netanyahu, the prime minister, who totally ignored the peace process.
Although rocket fire from Gaza has killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has been spared from suicide bombings, notably thanks to the separation barrier that encroaches on the West Bank, the main piece of what could be a Palestinian state, and which protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite their illegality in international law.
Netanyahu, whose Likud party merged with an even more hawkish party, that of leader Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the January 22 election, is on the bright side.
Why pamper these fucking Palestinians by giving them a state?
If they were to lead the West Bank, would they not launch rockets, as their compatriots did in Gaza?
It is best to keep them behind this wall and hit them as soon as they come out of the head.
Perhaps the hard-line supporters will win; but the Arab Spring may change the game.
Even if the Islamists taking power in Egypt and elsewhere do not appreciate Israel, their priority will be to address the problems in their own countries.
Israel's defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with the local superpower will not help the new Arab governments arrange their economies.
Mr. Morsi worked with Barack Obama to get a ceasefire, which bodes well -- and could mark the beginning of something.
Israelis should also think about the future.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination could create a powder keg that is doomed to explode one day in the Israeli-occupied territories – much like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression already weakens democracy in the Jewish state, and demographics exacerbate this problem as the Arab population grows.
The bloody missions against Gaza every two or three years to ring Hamas will have a diplomatic prize.
Both sides need to be pushed by those from the outside.
The answer remains the one advocated by the reasonable people on either side, and by most of the outside world and by this newspaper: two states, with a cession of territory by Israel in exchange for security.
One hope, small and short-term, is that the ceasefire will provide an opportunity for outsiders to stand up for this cause.
Egypt, which must now work to end the flow of arms to Gaza, as well as Turkey and Qatar, is better placed than ever to persuade Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state in line with the 1967 borders with exchanges of land and a shared Jerusalem.
Arabs from outside countries should also put pressure on Hamas and Fatah to unite.
This would contribute far more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the forthcoming proposal of a pseudo-state at the UN.
Obama also has every interest in Israel agreeing to negotiate.
During his first term, he did not present his own peace plan.
Back in the White House, he seems equally reluctant to establish one.
It's a very narrow vision.
