Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases released by the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
“I’m going to work another two years, because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French,” he promises in more than acceptable English.
Mishandled by life, this friendly and intelligent young man might be a tour guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, but instead he does the work of a mule.
It shares an unhealthy wood measure with other carriers, rises every day at two o'clock in the morning because the sulfur does not cease to spring at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater and lights up with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 carriers load the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable benefits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur extraction to save costs and does not provide any equipment to carriers who work on their own and are paid by weight.
In addition, they also do not receive a sub of the 30,000 rupees (2.50 euros) increase per camera, in addition to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros), which the guards of this natural park charge to tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This work is done for animals, not for humans,” protests Madrusin, a 42-year-old corpulent bearer who has been working in Kawah Ijen for thirty years, since he left college.
Able to carry up to 110 kilos, he assures that he will not stop working "as long as he can", as he needs money to raise his 3 sons, aged between 10 and 18 years.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although sulfur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the miners in the thick columns of smoke that come out of the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of suffering from serious diseases... to which are obviously added their usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and shoulders, deformed by the weights.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik, 53, can only carry 50 kilos.
