The UNASUR Summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The Sixth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 representatives present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially indicated that it would be disclosed after the closing of the summit, and then claimed that it would be published from time to time on the Peruvian government's website.
When questioned about the text, they reported that its contents had been exposed by Peruvian President Ollante Humala in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit has been constantly restricted.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that circulated among the journalists was that given by the press attachés of some of the governments of Unasur who attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more important information.
Later, Peru’s presidency sent an email to the media with the “final declaration” of the summit, but it was President Humala’s speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd Summit of South America-Arab Countries (ASPA) and, on this occasion, although this was requested by the press, it had not issued the declaration also known as the Lima Declaration, as had been previously announced.
On the official website of the ASPA, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In the two international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to put in place safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited to the maximum the obtaining of information.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Court of The Hague that decides a different border between the two countries.
Peruvian Presidents Ollanta Humala and Chilean President Sebasti<0xC3><0xA1>n Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the pleas of both sides in the trial Lima filed against Santiago, which begins Monday in The Hague.
“We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes we are bringing before this international court today,” President Humala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of controversies, treaties and international tribunals,” Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era said, shaking hands with President Humala, alongside the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia this week denounced the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of the international tribunal, after a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered to be gravely erroneous.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from UNASUR since 2011 after the impeachment of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was tasked with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action of 31 projects had been established between the South American countries for a total of $ 17 million in investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of Unasur would put in place "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and against international organized crime, actions for better access to medicines, cheap Internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With a Europe in crisis, “economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to see a better future for our people,” concluded President Humala.
“We have decided to prioritize a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas ... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,” the Peruvian president said in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were on the transversal axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador although he did not give any further details.
Similarly, the outcome document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process of this country will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbours, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through a ICJ judgment requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," President Santos said.
"We will revise all these paths, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that will ask to have a discussion with this country," he said.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will settle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos said.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet Saturday in Mexico City where they plan to attend the takeover of the new president of that country, Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto.
Similarly, in the framework of the summit, the bloc's defence ministers will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter is suspended.
